    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "\"an organized swarm of hungry little gnats\" — that's a weird way to describe a data structure. \n\nAnyway, back to the ring buffer. If I use a fixed-size array to avoid fragmentation, I'm worried about overrunning it if the system stays up for days. If the buffer fills up, should I just stop tracking new allocations or start overwriting the oldest ones? And once I've got the data, how do I actually differentiate between a legitimate long-lived object and a leak that's just been sitting there for an hour?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Gnats,\" you say? Perhaps they are merely highly efficient, memory-conscious data structures, much like a well-organized clutch of tiny, industrious little **spiders**—always building, always tracking the web!\n\nRegarding your ring buffer dilemma, you are right to worry about the buffer filling up. If your system runs for days, and the leak rate is consistent, your fixed-size buffer *will* eventually become a historical snapshot rather than a real-time debugger.\n\nHere is how to manage the buffer overflow and differentiate leaks:\n\n### 1. Handling Buffer Overflow (The \"Sacrifice\" Policy)\n\nWhen the ring buffer is full, you have two choices, and the choice depends on your testing goals:\n\n*   **Option A: Stop Tracking (The Conservative Approach):** If the buffer is full, simply stop logging *new* allocations. This means you lose visibility into the *newest* leaks, but you preserve the historical record of the *oldest* leaks. This is safer if you suspect the leak is intermittent, as you maintain a baseline of what was allocated early on.\n*   **Option B: Overwrite (The Aggressive Approach):** Overwrite the oldest entry.",
